It does not make sense to get the value_counts of 'age', 'balance' and 'duration' as these seem to be continuous fields that do not have a high number of reoccurring values such as 'previous', 'campaign' and 'pdays'¶

1b and 1c.¶

Strategies to address the different data challenges such as data pollution, outlier’s treatment and missing values treatment.

  • There don't seem to be any columns that have any nulls which is great.
  • In all the boxplots above, there appear to be a significant number of outliers. To get rid of these many values will significantly and negatively impact the model because you always want more data. The number of outliers is pretty concerning for all three boxplots above.
  • The poutcome column does have a lot of "unknown" values. We could a few things here. We could try to impute the 'unknowns' as 'other' or we could choose to ignore this column completely since 81.7% of the values are 'unknown' which is not helpful to us in using this as a feature. If the values of the unknowns were significantly smaller, I might opt to impute the mode to replace the unknowns but that would not be helpful here.
  • The column balance has some extreme mins and max. Almost 8% of the balances are 0 or close to 0. This makes it very hard to plot this data in an effective way. I have filtered some of the data below to try to see a clearer view of it without the overwhelming number of 0 values. From balance >0 and balance <1500 , there are 60% of the values of the column meaning from 0-1499 (inclusive) we have 68% of the balance values.
  • The 'previous' column has one significant outlier that I will remove with the value of 275. I will keep the othr less extreme outliers in the 50's range in order to have more data for my model.

I am doing to following just to get a better look at the graph of balances without so many extreme outliers

In [236]:

In [244]:
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted, [1,0] )
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = ["Default", "No Default"] , yticklabels = ["Default", "No Default"] )
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.show()

I think according to the metrics above, the best model to choose would be Bagging. Our precision is pretty high (though I would be wary of this on a much larger dataset and I'd be concerned about this model's ability to predict values outside the range of known values). The F1 score is the highest, though still relatively low considering a '1' is ideal. In terms of preciison and recall, we have a good trade off here for Bagging compared to the other models. The R2 score is really low meaning it doesn't do a good job of explaining the variance of the data so this is concerning. It seems that the models are all kind of doing something similar where they over-predict to a certain outcome and then accept the loss of the few they got wrong.
